{
  "text": "The increase of bone fragility with age is attributed primarily to bone density loss; however, changes of bone geometry may also influence BS [CITATION_1] . Therefore, vertebral size should be considered as a potential independent vertebral FR factor [CITATION_2] . An enlargement of the external bone diameter with age is the effect of periosteal bone apposition and endosteal resorption with thinning of the cortex [CITATION_3] . This is probably a mechanism to compensate for the decreased bone mass and the alterations in trabecular architecture [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] . Also, long-term bearing activity can result in an increase of the external diameter of bones supporting the load [CITATION_7] .",
